Immediate past Vice Chancellor of University of Osun (UNIOSUN), Prof Labo Popoola, has said that it was tough heading the institution. Popoola, however, said he left the varsity better than he met it. Speaking at a reception organised by his friends to honour him for his services at the institution, the ex-VC, who left office last November, said it was support from those he termed committed and honest staff that made him made substantial impact. He said: “With the support and assistance of God and a good number of officers and officials of the university, including the Chancellor, Dr. Folorunso Alakija, Pro-Chancellor, Mallam Yusuf Olaolu Alli, SAN, as well as other principal and other strategic officers, it wouldn’t have been easy for   Businessman joins governorship race     Oyo committed to quality infrastructure delivery     NDDC denies payment of N20b to ghost contractors   “But I want to tell you that I am happy I left the citadel of learning better that I met it in 2016 when I assumed office as the vice chancellor.” - Advertisement - A Professor of History and current Provost of Anti-Corruption Academy of Nigeria (ACAN) Prof. Tunde Babawale, described Popoola as a brilliant professor who was reputed for his incorruptibility. He said Popoola’s administrative style was marked by transparency, value for money, and accountability. Prof. Babawale recalled that the institution witnessed tremendous progress under Popoola’s five-year tenure as the third substantive vice-chancellor of the varsity. Vice Chancellor of UNIOSUN, Prof. Odunayo Adebooye, hailed his predecessor for the legacies of good governance he left behind. SPONSORED